1C pass 1S pass 2S pass 4S pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 1, chOption: N, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:0, nBasis: 2, nRot: 2, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "bdc6d4f2558ca00dede5dd2276cddb649b19d39f4f2a1ed39fda999d794c4a31"]
[Category "Declarer Play"]
[Difficulty "advanced"]
[SkillPath "declarer_play/elimination_plays"]
[Student "S"]
{North is to play 4\S. East leads the \DJ, covered by the \DQ and \DA. West returns a \D to the \DK.  

You still have two losers in the \H suit, so the question is which way you plan to finesse the \Cs. And of course the answer is that you don't plan to finesse them at all!

Pull trumps with the \SA, then \SK. Next ruff dummy's last \D.

Now exit with a \H. The defenders win this and take another \H trick, leaving this position.

They must now break the \C suit for you or give you a ruff-sluff. Of course you would ruff in dummy and discard a \C from the 3-card holding in your hand.

If West is the one who has to play a \C you just let it ride around to dummy's \C K J 10 3.  

If East is the one who has to play a \C you need to insert the \CT or \CJ from dummy.

In either case you will no longer have a \C loser.}
[Play "W"]DJ

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:AK875.A4.A63.AJ7 .J983.QJ974.Q853 T6432.K52.K8.KT2 QJ9.QT76.T52.964"]
